2026-02-10 19:40:31,059 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-3654ab7c-af30-4b81-9de3-f303cbfafe0f', 'json_data': {'input': 'Write copy for a Divento temporary exhibition listing.\n\nINPUTS\n- Title: CLING ! La bande dessinée parle cash, Exhibition, Musée de la Monnaie de Paris, Paris\n- Venue: The Musée de la Monnaie de Paris\n- City: Paris\n- Country: FR\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS (must pass)\n- Write as though the exhibition is already running; do not use future tense.\n- British English spelling.\n- Keep it casual, like talking to a friend, while staying factual and concrete.\n- Use natural rhythm and occasional contractions (it\'s, there\'s, don\'t) to avoid robotic phrasing.\n- Make the writing flow: vary sentence length, use smooth transitions between ideas, and avoid a rigid checklist feel.\n- Never use the first person.\n- Do not address the reader directly (no second person).\n- Do not use these words anywhere: You, visitor, visitors, located, feature, featured, showcase, blend, period, accessible.\n- Do not use em/en dash characters: — or –, except if they are part of the official exhibition title or venue name.\n- Do not include citations, links, or URLs.\n- Do not mention the exhibition dates anywhere.\n- Do not mention the visit duration/time-to-spend anywhere.\n- Spell out numbers one to ten in words (no digits 1–10).\n- Do not include the venue’s postal address (no street, postcode, or \'address is …\').\n- When mentioning the venue name in the copy, always write it with a leading \'The\' (capital T), matching: The Musée de la Monnaie de Paris.\n\nLONG (HTML)\n- Aim for 350 words.\n- Multiple paragraphs; wrap each paragraph in <p> tags.\n- Do not begin with the exhibition name, the venue name, or phrases like \'This exhibition\'.\n- Do not use formula openings such as: Across…, Through…, Inside…, At The venue…, In this show…\n- Use an informal, easy to read style.\n- Avoid concluding or summary-style final sentences.\nOPENING STRATEGY (CRITICAL FOR VARIATION)\n- Each exhibition description must open using a different narrative angle.\n- Anchor the opening on why the exhibition is worth a visit.\n- Do not prioritise the lay out of the exhibition.\n- Avoid openings that mention rooms, spaces, galleries, displays, labels, or layout structure.\n- Do not reuse opening sentence structure across exhibitions.\n- Avoid physical walkthrough descriptions or layout framing.\n- Avoid openings about rooms, galleries, spaces, layout, organisation, labels/interpretation panels, or sequences such as first/next/final.\n- Include naturally: one highlight, two don\'t-miss elements, and one hidden gem.\n- Mention at least three specific works, artists, or items when possible.\n- Use strong verbs, concrete nouns, active voice; cut filler.\n- No brochure-style language, clichés, or exaggerated adjectives.\n\nSHORT\n- Maximum 164 characters.\n- Must include a verb.\n- Must not repeat the exhibition name.\n- Must not repeat the phrasing or start of the long description.\n\n- Do not prioritise the lay out of the exhibition.\n- The short description MUST NOT focus on rooms, spaces, galleries, displays, labels, or layout structure.\n- Also avoid: exhibition organisation, interpretation panels, sequences such as first/next/final, or physical walkthrough descriptions.\n- Do not start the short description with \'Explore\'.\nOUTPUT\nRATING\n- Add a numeric rating for this exhibition (integer 1–4) using this scale:\n  4 = must see\n  3 = very solid if you care about the field\n  2 = niche / depends on your interests\n  1 = honestly skippable unless you’re nearby or researching\n\nOUTPUT\n- Return ONLY a JSON object with exactly the keys \'short\', \'long\', and \'rating\'.\n- Both \'short\' and \'long\' must be non-empty strings.\n\nPREVIOUS OUTPUT (JSON)\n{"short": "Comics get sharp about cash at The Musée de la Monnaie de Paris, with biting satire, rare original art, and real coins close by.", "long": "<p>Money makes great drama: greed, wishful thinking, tiny everyday transactions that somehow turn into big problems. That’s why comic artists keep coming back to cash, whether they’re mocking bosses, spinning heist plots, or just drawing the satisfying clink of coins. The whole thing feels immediate here, with jokes that land quickly and images that stick.</p>\\n<p>CLING ! La bande dessinée parle cash is running at The Musée de la Monnaie de Paris in Paris, France, and it takes the language of comics seriously: bold lines, sharp timing, and a lot of nerve. It’s not just gags about being broke, either. The exhibition keeps circling back to how money is made, how it moves, and who gets squeezed when it doesn’t.</p>\\n<p>The highlight is seeing original comic art handle money as a character in its own right. Pages and drawings associated with names like Hergé, Moebius, and Marjane Satrapi bring very different moods, from deadpan clarity to dreamlike unease to blunt autobiography. Close-up ink work turns banknotes into patterns, coins into symbols, and receipts into plot twists.</p>\\n<p>Two can’t-miss elements stand out. One is the run of stories and images about fraud and counterfeiting, paired with real tools and know-how from the world of minting and engraving. The other is the punchy social commentary, where spending, wages, inflation, and status get torn apart with humour that still bites. Artists linked to Franco-Belgian staples like Goscinny and Uderzo sit comfortably alongside more political voices such as Enki Bilal.</p>\\n<p>A hidden gem is the quieter material around sound effects and small transactions, the kind that usually sit in the corner of a panel: the drawn “cling” of coins, the scribbled totals, the petty cash tin that says more about a life than a speech ever could. It’s the sort of detail that makes the jokes sharper and the stakes feel oddly real.</p>", "rating": 3}\n\nFix these issues:\n- copy includes part of the venue postal address\nReturn ONLY the corrected JSON object.\n', 'max_output_tokens': 2500, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_exhibition_copy', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}, 'rating': {'type': 'integer', 'enum': [1, 2, 3, 4]}}, 'required': ['short', 'long', 'rating']}}}}}
