2026-02-10 19:42:02,971 DEBUG openai._base_client: Request options: {'method': 'post', 'url': '/responses', 'files': None, 'idempotency_key': 'stainless-python-retry-87348d6d-89fb-4a30-aea2-c8e854c1bf77', 'json_data': {'input': "Translate the following Divento temporary exhibition content.\n\nRules (follow exactly):\n- Return ONLY a JSON object matching the provided schema.\n- Do not add citations, links, or URLs.\n- Avoid em/en dash characters (— or –); rewrite with commas or parentheses.\n- Keep all HTML tags intact in 'long' and return valid HTML.\n- Do NOT add extra blank lines/newlines.\n- For 'short': maximum 164 characters in the target language, keep natural phrasing.\n- For 'name': translate only what should be translated; keep proper nouns/titles as appropriate.\n- For zh-CN: translate ALL prose into Simplified Chinese; Latin script is allowed ONLY for proper nouns and official artwork/series titles.\n\nEnglish inputs:\n- name_en: GIOVANNI SEGANTINI, Exhibition, Musée Marmottan Monet, Paris: 29 April-16 August 2026\n- short_en: Segantini’s Divisionist mountain scenes glow in Paris, pairing tough rural life with intimate motherhood and unsettling symbolism.\nlong_en_html:\n<p>Alpine light can feel like a moral argument in paint, and that’s the pull of the Giovanni Segantini exhibition running in Paris right now. The colour doesn’t sit politely on the surface; it breaks into tiny strokes that make snow glare, grass shimmer, and faces look as if they’ve been weathered by real wind.</p><p>Segantini’s world is rural and unsentimental, but it’s never cold. There’s tenderness in the way he handles everyday labour, animals, and family bonds, and there’s also a hard edge that tips into Symbolism when the subject turns to guilt, desire, or fate. That tension keeps things lively: one moment it’s all sunlit pasture, the next it’s a scene that quietly judges the viewer.</p><p>The highlight is the group of high-altitude canvases where the paint itself seems to vibrate, turning mountain air into something almost physical. One of the don’t-miss threads is the mother-and-child imagery, built from close observation rather than syrupy sentiment, with warm interior lamplight set against a harsher outdoors. The other don’t-miss is the darker, allegorical strain, where bodies, landscape, and conscience get tangled up in ways that feel surprisingly modern.</p><p>It’s also a good chance to get close to how he worked. Divisionism can sound like theory, but the drawings and studies make it practical: charcoal and pencil notes that pin down a shoulder, the angle of a neck, or the weight of a sheep before colour does the rest. A hidden gem comes in the quieter documentary material, including correspondence tied to his circle, which brings out the stubborn discipline behind the luminous finish.</p><p>Seen at The Musée Marmottan Monet, the show lands nicely in a city already attuned to painting light, but Segantini’s light has different stakes. Even the smallest animal study carries a bracing kind of attention, as if nothing ordinary is allowed to stay ordinary for long.</p>\n", 'max_output_tokens': 9000, 'model': 'gpt-5.2', 'reasoning': {'effort': 'medium'}, 'text': {'verbosity': 'low', 'format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'name': 'temp_translation_bundle', 'strict': True, 'schema': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'fr': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}, 'es': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}, 'it': {'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False, 'properties': {'name': {'type': 'string'}, 'short': {'type': 'string'}, 'long': {'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['name', 'short', 'long']}, 'ru': {'type': 'object